description._content: Zebra Crossing, Street Photography from New Delhi

A young man roasts peanuts at his stand on a portion of Old Delhi's normally busy Chandni Chowk that is closed for construction. The man on the left is carrying a bag from McDonald's, which now has a location just down the road. The man in the background on the right is giving away paper hats for the Aam Aadmi Party, which scored an upset win over the ruling BJP in Delhi's elections days later.
A traffic jam on Chandni Chowk in Old Delhi gives people a chance to get to know the neighbours as traffic inches along. These boys were amused by me and I found them amusing too.

When I photographed this cow on a busy street in Old Delhi, this man told me it was his cow and I owed him some kind of royalties. I agreed to pay him a few rupees if he would pose for a picture with his cow. The cow seemed a bit awkward about the arrangement. Cows no longer walk freely on the streets of Delhi as they did when I visited India in the 1970s, but outside of Delhi they wander as freely as ever.

My hotel room balcony overlooked the narrow and busy street of Main Bazar in New Delhi. There was a constant sound of honking horns and ringing bells as cars, motorcycles, rickshaws bicycles, pedestrians and pushcarts all competed for their bit of street.

Yes , a Mosque is a place of worship.

Early morning at old delhi, India

Chandni Chowk, Old Delhi, India

Chandni Chowk (Hindi: चांदनी चौक, Urdu: چاندنی چوک‎), originally meaning "moonlit square" or "moonlit market", is one of the oldest and busiest markets in Old Delhi, now in central north Delhi, India. Built in the 17th century by the Mughal emperor of India Shah Jahan, and designed by his daughter Jahan Ara, the market was once divided by canals (now closed) to reflect moonlight, and it remains one of India's largest wholesale markets.

From a visit to New Delhi, March 2015. 

Dominion Columns along the promenade - 4 in number, given by the dominions of the former British Empire -  Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and South Africa - each with a bronze ship on top. Supposedly a symbol of the Raj's ties with Oceanic trade.

Place I Street, Near Jama Masjid, New Delhi “Still images can be moving and moving images can be still. Both meet within sound scape” ~ Chien-Chi Chang

Woman working at the restoration of Jantar Mantar observatory in New Delhi, India. The Jantar Mantar is located in the modern city of New Delhi. It consists of 13 architectural astronomy instruments. The site is one of five built by Maharaja Jai Singh II of Jaipur, from 1724 onwards, as he was given by Mughal emperor Muhammad Shah the task of revising the calendar and astronomical tables. The primary purpose of the observatory was to compile astronomical tables, and to predict the times and movements of the sun, moon and planets. Chadni Chowk is pretty busy but its a great place to visit.
©AZRIAZAHAR

Stranger no. 52 | New Delhi, India | December 2015 “I moved to Delhi in 1984 in search for better job opportunities. This is my home now though my heart yearns for Kolkata (Calcutta, West Bengal). When the train is on time it takes approximately 34 hours to reach Bengal but I am all too happy to make this journey few times a year to see my family.” This picture is #51 in my 100 strangers project. Thank you Deepak for being a part of it. Find out more about the project and see pictures taken by other photographers at the 100 Strangers Flickr Group Page Facebook | Twitter | Instagram | Tumblr © All rights reserved.
